Your approach (each thread loads its own blur neighborhood) has a fundamental problem: threads overlap massively. Thread (0,0) and thread (1,0) both try to load many of the same shared memory cells, causing races with no guarantee of correctness.

The flat-index pattern
The idea is to treat the 2D block of threads as a 1D array of workers, and the 2D shared memory tile as a 1D array of work items, then distribute evenly:


Total shared memory cells: (TILE_WIDTH + 2*BLUR_SIZE)^2  = 24*24 = 576
Total threads per block:    TILE_WIDTH^2                  = 16*16 = 256
So each thread loads ~2.25 cells on average. You give each thread a starting index and step by the total thread count:


flat_thread = threadIdx.y * TILE_WIDTH + threadIdx.x   // 0..255

for (int i = flat_thread; i < (TILE_WIDTH+2*BLUR_SIZE)*(TILE_WIDTH+2*BLUR_SIZE); i += TILE_WIDTH*TILE_WIDTH) {
    // convert flat index i back to 2D shared memory coordinates
    int s_row = i / (TILE_WIDTH + 2*BLUR_SIZE);
    int s_col = i % (TILE_WIDTH + 2*BLUR_SIZE);
    
    // convert shared memory coords to global image coords
    int g_row = blockIdx.y * TILE_WIDTH + s_row - BLUR_SIZE;
    int g_col = blockIdx.x * TILE_WIDTH + s_col - BLUR_SIZE;
    
    // bounds check, then load (or store 0 for out-of-bounds)
    if (g_row >= 0 && g_row < height && g_col >= 0 && g_col < width)
        ds_in_border[s_row][s_col] = in[g_row * width + g_col];
    else
        ds_in_border[s_row][s_col] = {0, 0, 0};
}
With 576 cells and 256 threads: threads 0–63 each load 3 cells, threads 64–255 each load 2 cells. Every cell gets loaded by exactly one thread — no races.

