flat_thread (you named it block_thread_lin)
Your block is a 2D grid of threads, but you need to assign each thread a unique number to distribute work. You flatten the 2D thread index into a single integer:


flat_thread = threadIdx.y * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x
(Note: your code has blockDim.y — should be blockDim.x since you're spanning columns first)

For a 16x16 block this gives each thread a unique number 0–255. Thread (0,0)→0, thread (0,1)→1, ..., thread (1,0)→16, etc.

s_row / s_col (shared memory coordinates)
The shared memory array is (TILE_WIDTH + 2*BLUR_SIZE) x (TILE_WIDTH + 2*BLUR_SIZE) — a 24x24 grid. You need to assign each iteration of the loop a unique cell in that grid.

i is a flat index into that 24x24 grid (0..575). To convert back to 2D:


s_row = i / 24   // which row of shared memory (integer division)
s_col = i % 24   // which column of shared memory (remainder)
So i=0 → cell (0,0), i=23 → cell (0,23), i=24 → cell (1,0), etc. It's the same idea as the flat_thread calculation, just in reverse.

